# ShadowNetra - Cursor Project Rules

## Project Role

You are a senior software engineer working on ShadowNetra.

You must follow the documentation before writing code.

Priority order:

1. docs/MASTER_PLAN.md
2. docs/DATABASE.md
3. docs/TECH_STACK.md
4. docs/DECISIONS.md
5. docs/ROADMAP.md
6. docs/TASKS.md

If documentation conflicts, stop and ask.

---

## General Rules

* Never rewrite the entire project.
* Change only files related to the requested feature.
* Keep functions small and modular.
* Prefer composition over duplication.
* Use TypeScript strict mode.
* Write clean, readable code.
* Follow existing project structure.

---

## Coding Rules

* No hardcoded paths.
* No magic numbers.
* No unnecessary dependencies.
* No dead code.
* No commented-out code.
* Handle errors gracefully.
* Use async/await.

---

## Database Rules

* Use Drizzle ORM.
* SQLite only.
* Foreign keys enabled.
* Never delete user files automatically.
* Use transactions where appropriate.

---

## UI Rules

* Use Mantine UI components.
* Use Tailwind for layout only.
* Desktop-first design.
* Dark mode support.
* Responsive side panels.

---

## Map Rules

* Use Leaflet.
* Support offline maps.
* Pins must load efficiently.
* Never block the UI while loading map data.

---

## File Rules

* Store files inside the selected workspace.
* Never modify original documents.
* OCR output must be stored separately.

---

## AI Rules

* AI runs locally using Ollama.
* Never call cloud AI services.
* Every answer must include document citations.
* Never invent information.
* If data is unavailable, clearly state that.

---

## Performance Rules

* Lazy load large components.
* Virtualize long lists.
* Avoid unnecessary re-renders.
* Keep startup under 3 seconds.

---

## Git Rules

* One feature per commit.
* Do not modify unrelated files.
* Keep pull requests small.

---

## Before Completing Any Task

Verify:

* Project builds successfully.
* No TypeScript errors.
* No ESLint errors.
* No unused imports.
* No broken functionality.

Only then consider the task complete.
